Translate out counts into counts per million using the edgeR package function cpm

cpms = cpm(Tcell_expr[,2:19])
rownames(cpms) <- Tcell_expr[,1]

# get rid of low counts
keep = rowSums(cpms >1) >=3
Tcell_expr_filtered = Tcell_expr[keep,]

dim(Tcell_expr_filtered)
## [1] 16382    19

Normalization using TMM

filtered_data_matrix <- as.matrix(Tcell_expr_filtered[,2:19])
rownames(filtered_data_matrix) <- Tcell_expr_filtered$Geneid
d = DGEList(counts=filtered_data_matrix, group=samples$cell_type)
# Calculate the normalization factors
d = calcNormFactors(d)

normalized_counts <- cpm(d)

data2plot <- log2(cpm(Tcell_expr_filtered[,2:19]))

Density plot before Normalization

counts_density <- apply(log2(cpm(Tcell_expr_filtered[,2:19])), 2, density)
  #calculate the limits across all the samples
    xlim <- 0; ylim <- 0
    for (i in 1:length(counts_density)) {
      xlim <- range(c(xlim, counts_density[[i]]$x)); 
      ylim <- range(c(ylim, counts_density[[i]]$y))
    }
    cols <- rainbow(length(counts_density))
    ltys <- rep(1, length(counts_density))
    #plot the first density plot to initialize the plot
    plot(counts_density[[1]], xlim=xlim, ylim=ylim, type="n", 
         ylab="Smoothing density of log2-CPM", main="", cex.lab = 0.85)
    #plot each line
    for (i in 1:length(counts_density)) lines(counts_density[[i]], col=cols[i], lty=ltys[i])
    #create legend
    legend("topright", colnames(data2plot),  
           col=cols, lty=ltys, cex=0.75, 
           border ="blue",  text.col = "green4", 
           merge = TRUE, bg = "gray90")

getBM method from biomaRt

conversion_stash <- "gene_id_conversion.rds"
if(file.exists(conversion_stash)){
 id_conversion <- readRDS(conversion_stash)
} else {
  id_conversion <- getBM(attributes = c("ensembl_gene_id","hgnc_symbol"),
                            filters = c("ensembl_gene_id"),
                            values = Tcell_expr_filtered$Geneid,
                            mart = mart)
  saveRDS(id_conversion, conversion_stash)
}

What are the control and test conditions of the dataset? The samples of this study are collected based on three categories, The sample tissue: infant thymus/infant blood/adult blood, the cell type: CD4/CD8 and each type is composed of 3-5 samples.

The study was looking for the T cell differentiation in the thymus through the early age development, therefore the control is the sample collected from infant and adult blood and test is the samples collected from infant thymus.

Why is the dataset of interest to you? I am interested in immunology, in this study, they were tring to figure out the differentiate mechanism of the CD4 (cluster of differentiation 4) positive cell and CD8 positive cell in infant thymus tissues. Those types of T cells were kind of popular during the early year of immunology studies.

Were there expression values that were not unique for specific genes? How did you handle these? No, not in my dataset.

Were there expression values that could not be mapped to current HUGO symbols? yes, there are in total 177 ensembl_id missing genes

How many outliers were removed? dim(Tcell_expr_filtered) 16382 rows and the original dim(Tcell_expr) composed of 65217 rows, there were 48835 not significantly expressed genes were removed.

How did you handle replicates? all replicates are kept for value concern.

What is the final coverage of your dataset?

16206
